The rest of the paper is organized as follows.
In Section 2, we review the literature to put our work in comparative perspectives.
In Section 3, we provide empirical fat-tailed evidence for FL to further motivate this work.
Section 4 presents our 𝖥𝖠𝖳𝖥𝖠𝖳\mathsf{FAT}-𝖢𝗅𝗂𝗉𝗉𝗂𝗇𝗀𝖢𝗅𝗂𝗉𝗉𝗂𝗇𝗀\mathsf{Clipping}~{}algorithms and their convergence analyses.
Section 5 presents numerical results and Section 6 concludes this paper.
Due to space limitation, all proof details and some experiments are provided in the supplementary material.

We run a convolutional neural network (CNN) model on CIFAR-10 dataset using FedAvg. The CNN architecture is shown in Table 2.
To simulate data heterogeneity across clients, we manually distribute the the data to each client in a label-based partition.
Specifically, we split the data according to the classes (p𝑝p) of images that each client has.
Then, we randomly distribute these partitioned data to m=100𝑚100m=100 clients such that each client has only p𝑝p classes of images in both training and test data, which causes the heterogeneity of data among different clients.
For example, for p=10𝑝10p=10, each client contains training/test data samples with ten classes.
Since CIFAR-10 has 101010 classes of images, p=10𝑝10p=10 is the nearly i.i.d case.
For the remaining p𝑝p, each client contains data samples with class p𝑝p. Therefore, the classes (p𝑝p) of images in each client’s local dataset can be used to represent the non-i.i.d. degree.
The smaller the p𝑝p-value, the more heterogeneous the data between clients.
